{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"The substance of things unseen."},{"time":3000,"text":"Cities, past and future."},{"time":6000,"text":"In Oxford, perhaps\nwe can use Lewis Carroll"},{"time":10000,"text":"and look in the looking glass\nthat is New York City"},{"time":13000,"text":"to try and see our true selves,"},{"time":16000,"text":"or perhaps pass through to another world."},{"time":19000,"text":"Or, in the words of F. Scott Fitzgerald,"},{"time":22000,"text":"\"As the moon rose higher,"},{"time":24000,"text":"the inessential houses began to melt away"},{"time":27000,"text":"until gradually I became\naware of the old island"},{"time":29000,"text":"here that once flowered\nfor Dutch sailors' eyes,"},{"time":32000,"text":"a fresh green breast of the new world.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":35000,"text":"My colleagues and I\nhave been working for 10 years"},{"time":37000,"text":"to rediscover this lost world"},{"time":40000,"text":"in a project we call\nThe Mannahatta Project."},{"time":43000,"text":"We're trying to discover\nwhat Henry Hudson would have seen"},{"time":45000,"text":"on the afternoon of September 12th, 1609,"},{"time":48000,"text":"when he sailed into New York harbor."},{"time":51000,"text":"And I'd like to tell you\nthe story in three acts,"},{"time":53000,"text":"and if I have time still, an epilogue."}]},{"cues":[{"time":56000,"text":"So, Act I: A Map Found."},{"time":58000,"text":"So, I didn't grow up in New York."},{"time":60000,"text":"I grew up out west in the\nSierra Nevada Mountains, like you see here,"},{"time":63000,"text":"in the Red Rock Canyon."},{"time":65000,"text":"And from these early\nexperiences as a child"},{"time":67000,"text":"I learned to love landscapes."},{"time":69000,"text":"And so when it became time\nfor me to do my graduate studies,"},{"time":71000,"text":"I studied this emerging field\nof landscape ecology."},{"time":75000,"text":"Landscape ecology concerns itself"},{"time":77000,"text":"with how the stream and the meadow\nand the forest and the cliffs"},{"time":81000,"text":"make habitats for plants and animals."},{"time":83000,"text":"This experience and this training"},{"time":85000,"text":"lead me to get a wonderful job\nwith the Wildlife Conservation Society,"},{"time":88000,"text":"which works to save wildlife\nand wild places all over the world."},{"time":91000,"text":"And over the last decade,"},{"time":93000,"text":"I traveled to over 40 countries"},{"time":95000,"text":"to see jaguars and bears and elephants"},{"time":97000,"text":"and tigers and rhinos."}]},{"cues":[{"time":99000,"text":"But every time I would return\nfrom my trips I'd return back to New York City."},{"time":102000,"text":"And on my weekends I would go up,\njust like all the other tourists,"},{"time":105000,"text":"to the top of the Empire State Building,"},{"time":107000,"text":"and I'd look down on this landscape,\non these ecosystems,"},{"time":110000,"text":"and I'd wonder, \"How does this landscape"},{"time":112000,"text":"work to make habitat\nfor plants and animals?"},{"time":114000,"text":"How does it work to make habitat\nfor animals like me?\""},{"time":118000,"text":"I'd go to Times Square and I'd look\nat the amazing ladies on the wall,"},{"time":122000,"text":"and wonder why nobody is looking\nat the historical figures just behind them."},{"time":127000,"text":"I'd go to Central Park and see\nthe rolling topography of Central Park"},{"time":130000,"text":"come up against the abrupt and sheer"},{"time":132000,"text":"topography of midtown Manhattan."}]},{"cues":[{"time":136000,"text":"I started reading about the history\nand the geography in New York City."},{"time":139000,"text":"I read that New York City\nwas the first mega-city,"},{"time":141000,"text":"a city of 10 million people\nor more, in 1950."},{"time":145000,"text":"I started seeing paintings like this."},{"time":147000,"text":"For those of you who are from New York,"},{"time":149000,"text":"this is 125th street\nunder the West Side Highway."},{"time":152000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":154000,"text":"It was once a beach.\nAnd this painting"},{"time":156000,"text":"has John James Audubon,\nthe painter, sitting on the rock."},{"time":159000,"text":"And it's looking up on the wooded heights\nof Washington Heights"},{"time":161000,"text":"to Jeffrey's Hook, where the George\nWashington Bridge goes across today."}]},{"cues":[{"time":165000,"text":"Or this painting, from the 1740s,\nfrom Greenwich Village."},{"time":168000,"text":"Those are two students at King's College --\nlater Columbia University --"},{"time":171000,"text":"sitting on a hill, overlooking a valley."},{"time":174000,"text":"And so I'd go down to Greenwich\nVillage and I'd look for this hill,"},{"time":177000,"text":"and I couldn't find it.\nAnd I couldn't find that palm tree."},{"time":180000,"text":"What's that palm tree doing there?"},{"time":182000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":183000,"text":"So, it was in the course of these investigations\nthat I ran into a map."},{"time":186000,"text":"And it's this map you see here."},{"time":188000,"text":"It's held in a geographic information system"},{"time":190000,"text":"which allows me to zoom in."},{"time":192000,"text":"This map isn't from Hudson's time,\nbut from the American Revolution,"},{"time":195000,"text":"170 years later, made by\nBritish military cartographers"},{"time":199000,"text":"during the occupation of New York City."},{"time":201000,"text":"And it's a remarkable map.\nIt's in the National Archives here in Kew."},{"time":205000,"text":"And it's 10 feet long and\nthree and a half feet wide."}]},{"cues":[{"time":207000,"text":"And if I zoom in to lower Manhattan"},{"time":210000,"text":"you can see the extent\nof New York City as it was,"},{"time":212000,"text":"right at the end of the American Revolution."},{"time":214000,"text":"Here's Bowling Green.\nAnd here's Broadway."},{"time":217000,"text":"And this is City Hall Park."},{"time":219000,"text":"So the city basically extended\nto City Hall Park."},{"time":222000,"text":"And just beyond it you can see features"},{"time":224000,"text":"that have vanished,\nthings that have disappeared."},{"time":226000,"text":"This is the Collect Pond, which was\nthe fresh water source for New York City"},{"time":229000,"text":"for its first 200 years,"},{"time":231000,"text":"and for the Native Americans\nfor thousands of years before that."},{"time":234000,"text":"You can see the Lispenard Meadows"},{"time":236000,"text":"draining down through here,\nthrough what is TriBeCa now,"},{"time":238000,"text":"and the beaches that\ncome up from the Battery,"},{"time":240000,"text":"all the way to 42nd St."}]},{"cues":[{"time":242000,"text":"This map was made for military reasons."},{"time":245000,"text":"They're mapping the roads,\nthe buildings, these fortifications"},{"time":247000,"text":"that they built."},{"time":249000,"text":"But they're also mapping\nthings of ecological interest,"},{"time":251000,"text":"also military interest: the hills,"},{"time":253000,"text":"the marshes, the streams."},{"time":256000,"text":"This is Richmond Hill,\nand Minetta Water,"},{"time":258000,"text":"which used to run its way\nthrough Greenwich Village."},{"time":261000,"text":"Or the swamp at Gramercy Park, right here."},{"time":266000,"text":"Or Murray Hill.\nAnd this is the Murrays' house"},{"time":268000,"text":"on Murray Hill, 200 years ago."},{"time":271000,"text":"Here is Times Square,"},{"time":274000,"text":"the two streams that came\ntogether to make a wetland"},{"time":276000,"text":"in Times Square, as it was\nat the end of the American Revolution."}]},{"cues":[{"time":281000,"text":"So I saw this remarkable map in a book."},{"time":283000,"text":"And I thought to myself, \"You know,\nif I could georeference this map,"},{"time":287000,"text":"if I could place this map\nin the grid of the city today,"},{"time":290000,"text":"I could find these lost features"},{"time":292000,"text":"of the city,"},{"time":294000,"text":"in the block-by-block\ngeography that people know,"},{"time":297000,"text":"the geography of where people\ngo to work, and where they go to live,"},{"time":300000,"text":"and where they like to eat.\""},{"time":302000,"text":"So, after some work\nwe were able to georeference it,"},{"time":304000,"text":"which allows us to put\nthe modern streets on the city,"},{"time":307000,"text":"and the buildings, and the open spaces,"},{"time":312000,"text":"so that we can zoom in\nto where the Collect Pond is."},{"time":317000,"text":"We can digitize the Collect\nPond and the streams,"},{"time":321000,"text":"and see where they actually are\nin the geography of the city today."},{"time":326000,"text":"So this is fun\nfor finding where things are"},{"time":329000,"text":"relative to the old topography."}]},{"cues":[{"time":334000,"text":"But I had another idea about this map."},{"time":336000,"text":"If we take away the streets,\nand if we take away the buildings,"},{"time":339000,"text":"and if we take away the open spaces,"},{"time":341000,"text":"then we could take this map."},{"time":343000,"text":"If we pull off the 18th century features"},{"time":345000,"text":"we could drive it back in time."},{"time":347000,"text":"We could drive it back\nto its ecological fundamentals:"},{"time":351000,"text":"to the hills, to the streams,"},{"time":353000,"text":"to the basic hydrology\nand shoreline, to the beaches,"},{"time":357000,"text":"the basic aspects that\nmake the ecological landscape."}]},{"cues":[{"time":361000,"text":"Then, if we added maps\nlike the geology, the bedrock geology,"},{"time":364000,"text":"and the surface geology,\nwhat the glaciers leave,"},{"time":367000,"text":"if we make the soil map,"},{"time":369000,"text":"with the 17 soil classes,"},{"time":372000,"text":"that are defined by\nthe National Conservation Service,"},{"time":375000,"text":"if we make a digital elevation model"},{"time":377000,"text":"of the topography\nthat tells us how high the hills were,"},{"time":380000,"text":"then we can calculate the slopes."},{"time":383000,"text":"We can calculate the aspect."},{"time":386000,"text":"We can calculate the\nwinter wind exposure --"},{"time":388000,"text":"so, which way the winter\nwinds blow across the landscape."},{"time":390000,"text":"The white areas on this map\nare the places protected from the winter winds."}]},{"cues":[{"time":395000,"text":"We compiled all the information\nabout where the Native Americans were, the Lenape."},{"time":398000,"text":"And we built a probability map\nof where they might have been."},{"time":402000,"text":"So, the red areas\non this map indicate the places"},{"time":404000,"text":"that are best for human\nsustainability on Manhattan,"},{"time":406000,"text":"places that are close to water,"},{"time":408000,"text":"places that are near the harbor to fish,"},{"time":410000,"text":"places protected from the winter winds."},{"time":415000,"text":"We know that there was a Lenape settlement"},{"time":417000,"text":"down here by the Collect Pond."},{"time":420000,"text":"And we knew that they\nplanted a kind of horticulture,"},{"time":422000,"text":"that they grew these beautiful gardens\nof corn, beans, and squash,"},{"time":425000,"text":"the \"Three Sisters\" garden."}]},{"cues":[{"time":427000,"text":"So, we built a model that explains\nwhere those fields might have been."},{"time":431000,"text":"And the old fields, the successional fields that go."},{"time":433000,"text":"And we might think of these as abandoned."},{"time":435000,"text":"But, in fact, they're grassland habitats"},{"time":437000,"text":"for grassland birds and plants."},{"time":439000,"text":"And they have become\nsuccessional shrub lands,"},{"time":442000,"text":"and these then mix in\nto a map of all the ecological communities."},{"time":446000,"text":"And it turns out that Manhattan\nhad 55 different ecosystem types."},{"time":450000,"text":"You can think of these as neighborhoods,"},{"time":452000,"text":"as distinctive as TriBeCa\nand the Upper East Side and Inwood --"},{"time":457000,"text":"that these are the forest and the wetlands"},{"time":459000,"text":"and the marine communities, the beaches."}]},{"cues":[{"time":462000,"text":"And 55 is a lot. On a per-area basis,"},{"time":465000,"text":"Manhattan had more ecological communities"},{"time":467000,"text":"per acre than Yosemite does,"},{"time":469000,"text":"than Yellowstone, than Amboseli."},{"time":472000,"text":"It was really an extraordinary landscape"},{"time":474000,"text":"that was capable of supporting\nan extraordinary biodiversity."}]},{"cues":[{"time":478000,"text":"So, Act II: A Home Reconstructed."},{"time":482000,"text":"So, we studied the fish and the frogs\nand the birds and the bees,"},{"time":486000,"text":"the 85 different kinds of fish\nthat were on Manhattan,"},{"time":489000,"text":"the Heath hens, the species\nthat aren't there anymore,"},{"time":493000,"text":"the beavers on all the streams,\nthe black bears,"},{"time":496000,"text":"and the Native Americans,\nto study how they used"},{"time":499000,"text":"and thought about their landscape."},{"time":501000,"text":"We wanted to try and map these.\nAnd to do that what we did"},{"time":504000,"text":"was we mapped their habitat needs."}]},{"cues":[{"time":506000,"text":"Where do they get their food?"},{"time":508000,"text":"Where do they get their water?\nWhere do they get their shelter?"},{"time":510000,"text":"Where do they get their\nreproductive resources?"},{"time":513000,"text":"To an ecologist, the intersection\nof these is habitat,"},{"time":516000,"text":"but to most people,\nthe intersection of these is their home."},{"time":521000,"text":"So, we would read in field guides,\nthe standard field guides"},{"time":523000,"text":"that maybe you have on your shelves,"},{"time":525000,"text":"you know, what beavers need is,\n\"A slowly meandering stream"},{"time":527000,"text":"with aspen trees and alders and willows,"},{"time":530000,"text":"near the water.\"\nThat's the best thing for a beaver."}]},{"cues":[{"time":532000,"text":"So we just started making a list."},{"time":534000,"text":"Here is the beaver.\nAnd here is the stream,"},{"time":536000,"text":"and the aspen and the alder\nand the willow."},{"time":538000,"text":"As if these were the maps\nthat we would need"},{"time":540000,"text":"to predict where you would find the beaver."},{"time":542000,"text":"Or the bog turtle, needing wet meadows\nand insects and sunny places."},{"time":546000,"text":"Or the bobcat, needing rabbits\nand beavers and den sites."},{"time":550000,"text":"And rapidly we started to realize\nthat beavers can be"},{"time":553000,"text":"something that a bobcat needs."},{"time":556000,"text":"But a beaver also needs things.\nAnd that having it"},{"time":558000,"text":"on either side means that\nwe can link it together,"},{"time":560000,"text":"that we can create the network"},{"time":562000,"text":"of the habitat relationships\nfor these species."}]},{"cues":[{"time":565000,"text":"Moreover, we realized\nthat you can start out"},{"time":567000,"text":"as being a beaver specialist,"},{"time":569000,"text":"but you can look up what an aspen needs."},{"time":571000,"text":"An aspen needs fire and dry soils."},{"time":574000,"text":"And you can look at\nwhat a wet meadow needs."},{"time":577000,"text":"And it need beavers\nto create the wetlands,"},{"time":579000,"text":"and maybe some other things."},{"time":581000,"text":"But you can also talk\nabout sunny places."},{"time":583000,"text":"So, what does a sunny place need?\nNot habitat per se."},{"time":586000,"text":"But what are the conditions\nthat make it possible?"},{"time":588000,"text":"Or fire. Or dry soils."},{"time":591000,"text":"And that you can put these\non a grid that's 1,000 columns long"},{"time":594000,"text":"across the top and 1,000 rows\ndown the other way."},{"time":597000,"text":"And then we can visualize\nthis data like a network,"},{"time":600000,"text":"like a social network."}]},{"cues":[{"time":602000,"text":"And this is the network\nof all the habitat relationships"},{"time":604000,"text":"of all the plants and animals\non Manhattan,"},{"time":606000,"text":"and everything they needed,"},{"time":608000,"text":"going back to the geology,"},{"time":610000,"text":"going back to time and space\nat the very core of the web."},{"time":613000,"text":"We call this the Muir Web.\nAnd if you zoom in on it it looks like this."},{"time":616000,"text":"Each point is a different species"},{"time":618000,"text":"or a different stream\nor a different soil type."},{"time":621000,"text":"And those little gray lines are the connections\nthat connect them together."},{"time":624000,"text":"They are the connections\nthat actually make nature resilient."},{"time":627000,"text":"And the structure of this\nis what makes nature work,"},{"time":631000,"text":"seen with all its parts."},{"time":633000,"text":"We call these Muir Webs\nafter the Scottish-American naturalist"},{"time":636000,"text":"John Muir, who said, \"When we try\nto pick out anything by itself,"},{"time":639000,"text":"we find that it's bound fast\nby a thousand invisible cords"},{"time":642000,"text":"that cannot be broken,\nto everything in the universe.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":646000,"text":"So then we took the Muir webs\nand we took them back to the maps."},{"time":649000,"text":"So if we wanted to go between 85th and 86th,"},{"time":651000,"text":"and Lex and Third,"},{"time":653000,"text":"maybe there was a stream in that block."},{"time":655000,"text":"And these would be the kind of trees\nthat might have been there,"},{"time":657000,"text":"and the flowers and the lichens\nand the mosses,"},{"time":661000,"text":"the butterflies, the fish in the stream,"},{"time":664000,"text":"the birds in the trees."},{"time":666000,"text":"Maybe a timber rattlesnake lived there."},{"time":668000,"text":"And perhaps a black bear walked by.\nAnd maybe Native Americans were there."},{"time":671000,"text":"And then we took this data."}]},{"cues":[{"time":673000,"text":"You can see this for yourself\non our website."},{"time":675000,"text":"You can zoom into\nany block on Manhattan,"},{"time":677000,"text":"and see what might have\nbeen there 400 years ago."},{"time":680000,"text":"And we used it to try\nand reveal a landscape"},{"time":683000,"text":"here in Act III."},{"time":685000,"text":"We used the tools they use in Hollywood"},{"time":687000,"text":"to make these fantastic landscapes\nthat we all see in the movies."}]},{"cues":[{"time":690000,"text":"And we tried to use it to visualize Third Avenue."},{"time":693000,"text":"So we would take the landscape\nand we would build up the topography."},{"time":697000,"text":"We'd lay on top of that the soils and the waters,\nand illuminate the landscape."},{"time":701000,"text":"We would lay on top of that\nthe map of the ecological communities."},{"time":704000,"text":"And feed into that the map of the species."},{"time":707000,"text":"So that we would actually take a photograph,"},{"time":709000,"text":"flying above Times Square,\nlooking toward the Hudson River,"},{"time":711000,"text":"waiting for Hudson to come."},{"time":713000,"text":"Using this technology, we can make these"},{"time":715000,"text":"fantastic georeferenced views."},{"time":717000,"text":"We can basically take a picture\nout of any window"},{"time":719000,"text":"on Manhattan and see what that landscape\nlooked like 400 years ago."}]},{"cues":[{"time":722000,"text":"This is the view from the East River,\nlooking up Murray Hill"},{"time":725000,"text":"at where the United Nations is today."},{"time":728000,"text":"This is the view looking\ndown the Hudson River,"},{"time":730000,"text":"with Manhattan on the left,\nand New Jersey out on the right,"},{"time":733000,"text":"looking out toward the Atlantic Ocean."},{"time":736000,"text":"This is the view over Times Square,"},{"time":738000,"text":"with the beaver pond there,\nlooking out toward the east."},{"time":742000,"text":"So we can see the Collect Pond,\nand Lispenard Marshes back behind."},{"time":746000,"text":"We can see the fields\nthat the Native Americans made."},{"time":749000,"text":"And we can see this\nin the geography of the city today."},{"time":753000,"text":"So when you're watching \"Law and Order,\"\nand the lawyers walk up the steps"},{"time":756000,"text":"they could have walked\nback down those steps"},{"time":758000,"text":"of the New York Court House,\nright into the Collect Pond,"},{"time":760000,"text":"400 years ago."}]},{"cues":[{"time":764000,"text":"So these images are the work\nof my friend and colleague,"},{"time":767000,"text":"Mark Boyer, who is here\nin the audience today."},{"time":769000,"text":"And I'd just like, if you would\ngive him a hand,"},{"time":771000,"text":"to call out for his fine work."},{"time":774000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":783000,"text":"There is such power in bringing\nscience and visualization together,"},{"time":786000,"text":"that we can create images like this,"},{"time":788000,"text":"perhaps looking on either\nside of a looking glass."},{"time":791000,"text":"And even though I've only\nhad a brief time to speak,"},{"time":793000,"text":"I hope you appreciate that\nMannahatta was a very special place."},{"time":796000,"text":"The place that you see here\non the left side"},{"time":799000,"text":"was interconnected.\nIt was based on this diversity."},{"time":801000,"text":"It had this resilience that is\nwhat we need in our modern world."}]},{"cues":[{"time":806000,"text":"But I wouldn't have you think\nthat I don't like the place"},{"time":809000,"text":"on the right, which I quite do.\nI've come to love the city"},{"time":812000,"text":"and its kind of diversity,\nand its resilience,"},{"time":814000,"text":"and its dependence on density\nand how we're connected together."},{"time":819000,"text":"In fact, that I see them\nas reflections of each other,"},{"time":823000,"text":"much as Lewis Carroll did\nin \"Through the Looking Glass.\""},{"time":826000,"text":"We can compare these two and hold them\nin our minds at the same time,"},{"time":830000,"text":"that they really are the same place,"},{"time":832000,"text":"that there is no way that cities\ncan escape from nature."},{"time":835000,"text":"And I think this is what we're learning\nabout building cities in the future."}]},{"cues":[{"time":839000,"text":"So if you'll allow me a brief epilogue,\nnot about the past,"},{"time":842000,"text":"but about 400 years from now,"},{"time":844000,"text":"what we're realizing is that"},{"time":846000,"text":"cities are habitats for people,"},{"time":848000,"text":"and need to supply what people need:"},{"time":850000,"text":"a sense of home, food, water, shelter,"},{"time":853000,"text":"reproductive resources,\nand a sense of meaning."},{"time":857000,"text":"This is the particular additional\nhabitat requirement of humanity."},{"time":860000,"text":"And so many of the talks here\nat TED are about meaning,"},{"time":863000,"text":"about bringing meaning to our lives"},{"time":865000,"text":"in all kinds of different ways, through technology,"},{"time":867000,"text":"through art, through science,"},{"time":869000,"text":"so much so that I think\nwe focus so much on"},{"time":872000,"text":"that side of our lives,\nthat we haven't given enough"},{"time":874000,"text":"attention to the food and the water\nand the shelter,"},{"time":877000,"text":"and what we need to raise the kids."}]},{"cues":[{"time":880000,"text":"So, how can we envision\nthe city of the future?"},{"time":883000,"text":"Well, what if we go\nto Madison Square Park,"},{"time":885000,"text":"and we imagine it without all the cars,"},{"time":888000,"text":"and bicycles instead"},{"time":890000,"text":"and large forests, and streams instead\nof sewers and storm drains?"},{"time":895000,"text":"What if we imagined the Upper East Side"},{"time":897000,"text":"with green roofs, and streams\nwinding through the city,"},{"time":901000,"text":"and windmills supplying\nthe power we need?"},{"time":904000,"text":"Or if we imagine the New York\nCity metropolitan area,"},{"time":907000,"text":"currently home to 12 million people,"},{"time":909000,"text":"but 12 million people in the future,\nperhaps living at the density of Manhattan,"},{"time":913000,"text":"in only 36 percent of the area,"},{"time":915000,"text":"with the areas in between\ncovered by farmland,"},{"time":918000,"text":"covered by wetlands,"},{"time":920000,"text":"covered by the marshes we need."}]},{"cues":[{"time":922000,"text":"This is the kind of future I think we need,"},{"time":925000,"text":"is a future that has the same diversity"},{"time":928000,"text":"and abundance and dynamism of Manhattan,"},{"time":931000,"text":"but that learns from the\nsustainability of the past,"},{"time":934000,"text":"of the ecology, the original ecology,\nof nature with all its parts."},{"time":939000,"text":"Thank you very much."},{"time":941000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}